Note:
C++ Semantic Analyzer - Type checking and semantic validation for C++ AST

This file performs comprehensive semantic analysis on C++ Abstract Syntax Trees including:
- Template instantiation and type deduction
- Class hierarchy analysis and virtual function resolution
- Overload resolution for functions and operators
- Name lookup in multiple scopes (local, class, namespace, template)
- RAII resource management validation
- Exception safety analysis
- const-correctness checking
- Access control validation (private, protected, public)
- Template specialization validation
- Auto type deduction (C++11+)
- Lambda expression analysis

Dependencies:
- cpp_parser.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cpp/cpp_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic Analyzer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
C++ semantic analysis is scope-, class-, and template-instantiation-sensitive.
Name lookup walks an explicit scope stack (function/block/class/namespace);
member lookup additionally consults class_hierarchy for base-class chains;
template instantiation needs a separate cache to avoid re-instantiating the
same template/args pair. Carrying these as fields on the analyzer keeps the
recursive walks state-free and allows save/restore on errors via a sticky
has_error flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
80-byte record (10 x i64 slots) at offsets 0..72: global_scope (Dict
name->CppSymbol), current_scope (Dict, top of stack), scope_stack (List of
Dict), class_hierarchy (Dict class_name->base_list), template_cache (Dict
template_id->instantiation), current_class (CppSymbol*), current_function
(CppSymbol*), template_context (TemplateContext*), error_message (owned
StringCore), has_error (sticky 0/1).
@End Implementation

Type called "CppSemanticAnalyzer":
    global_scope as Integer       Note: Global symbol table
    current_scope as Integer      Note: Current scope symbol table
    scope_stack as Integer        Note: Stack of scopes (list)
    class_hierarchy as Integer    Note: Class inheritance relationships
    template_cache as Integer     Note: Template instantiation cache
    current_class as Integer      Note: Current class being analyzed
    current_function as Integer   Note: Current function being analyzed
    template_context as Integer   Note: Current template instantiation context
    error_message as Integer      Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer          Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Symbol Table Entry for C++
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
C++ symbols carry more than just a name and type: function overloads require
a list of overloads at the same name, classes need template parameter lists,
and every symbol is positioned relative to its class and namespace for
qualified lookup (e.g., A::B::foo). The attributes slot packs access level,
storage class, virtual/static/const flags as a bitfield so all attribute
checks are O(1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
64-byte record (8 x i64) at offsets 0..56: name (StringCore), symbol_type
(one of CPP_SYMBOL_* constants), type_info (type AST node pointer),
attributes (packed bitfield), template_params (List of param nodes or 0
for non-templates), overloads (List of CppSymbol or 0 for non-functions),
class_context (CppSymbol* of enclosing class or 0), namespace_context
(StringCore qualified namespace path or 0 for global).
@End Implementation

Type called "CppSymbol":
    name as Integer               Note: Symbol name
    symbol_type as Integer        Note: Symbol type (variable, function, class, etc.)
    type_info as Integer          Note: Type information node
    attributes as Integer         Note: Access level, storage class, etc.
    template_params as Integer    Note: Template parameters (if template)
    overloads as Integer          Note: Function overload list
    class_context as Integer      Note: Class this symbol belongs to
    namespace_context as Integer  Note: Namespace this symbol belongs to
End Type

Note: Symbol types (extends C symbols)
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE as Integer is 1
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION as Integer is 2
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS as Integer is 3
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_NAMESPACE as Integer is 4
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_TEMPLATE as Integer is 5
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_TYPEDEF as Integer is 6
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_ENUM as Integer is 7
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_CONSTRUCTOR as Integer is 8
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_DESTRUCTOR as Integer is 9
Constant CPP_SYMBOL_OPERATOR as Integer is 10

Note: Access levels
Constant ACCESS_PRIVATE as Integer is 0
Constant ACCESS_PROTECTED as Integer is 1
Constant ACCESS_PUBLIC as Integer is 2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Template Instantiation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Template instantiation in C++ is recursive: a template can instantiate
another template, and template parameters from outer scopes must remain
visible inside inner instantiations. The context is therefore a linked list
via parent_context, with template_args holding the leaf binding map. The
depth counter is checked against a hard limit to fail fast on accidentally
divergent recursive templates (C++ standard mandates a limit of 17+).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record (3 x i64) at offsets 0/8/16: template_args (Dict param_name
-> argument AST node), parent_context (TemplateContext* of enclosing
instantiation or 0 for outermost), instantiation_depth (integer count
incremented on each nested push, used to enforce the instantiation limit).
@End Implementation

Type called "TemplateContext":
    template_args as Integer      Note: Template argument mappings
    parent_context as Integer     Note: Parent template context (for nested templates)
    instantiation_depth as Integer Note: Current instantiation depth
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs the analyzer and primes every required collection. Failure
of any sub-allocation must unwind cleanly because partial analyzers
would crash subsequent passes; each If chain frees previously created
collections before propagating the 0 return.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 80 bytes (10 slots). Returns 0 on outer allocation failure.
Creates global_scope (Dict), scope_stack (List), class_hierarchy
(Dict), template_cache (Dict) - each on failure tears down already-
created resources and returns 0. Stores pointers at offsets 0/8/16/24/32
(8 = current_scope = global_scope), zeroes remaining slots (40-72).
Pushes global_scope onto scope_stack so the analyzer always has at
least one scope to look up in. Returns the analyzer pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_cpp_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create C++ semantic analyzer with all necessary contexts

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize comprehensive semantic analyzer state including symbol tables,
    template caches, class hierarchies, and error tracking systems.
    @End Reasoning

    Let analyzer_size be 80  Note: CppSemanticAnalyzer: 10 fields × 8 bytes
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let global_scope be proc create from Dict
    If global_scope is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
        Return 0
    End If

    Let scope_stack be proc create from List
    If scope_stack is equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with global_scope
        proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
        Return 0
    End If

    Let class_hierarchy be proc create from Dict
    If class_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with global_scope
        proc destroy from List with scope_stack
        proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
        Return 0
    End If

    Let template_cache be proc create from Dict
    If template_cache is equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with global_scope
        proc destroy from List with scope_stack
        proc destroy from Dict with class_hierarchy
        proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, global_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, global_scope  Note: current_scope = global
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, scope_stack
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, class_hierarchy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, template_cache
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, 0  Note: current_class = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, 0  Note: current_function = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, 0  Note: template_context = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Add global scope to scope stack
    proc push from List with scope_stack, global_scope

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The analyzer owns four heap collections (global_scope, scope_stack,
class_hierarchy, template_cache) and one optional error string. Each
must be destroyed via its own destructor to free internal entries
before the analyzer struct itself is released.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if analyzer is 0 (idempotent). Reads each owned pointer
slot (0/16/24/32/64). Destroys each non-null collection via its
matching destructor (Dict.destroy / List.destroy). Deallocates the
error_message string if non-null. Finally deallocates the 80-byte
analyzer struct.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_cpp_semantic_analyzer" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy C++ semantic analyzer and free all resources

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let global_scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let class_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let template_cache be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64

    If global_scope is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with global_scope
    End If

    If scope_stack is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with scope_stack
    End If

    If class_hierarchy is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with class_hierarchy
    End If

    If template_cache is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with template_cache
    End If

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Semantic Analysis Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two-pass analysis is required because C++ allows forward references
within a translation unit (e.g. a class can reference another class
defined later in the same file). Pass 1 registers all top-level
symbols; pass 2 performs full analysis with a complete symbol table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards both analyzer and program_node; on the latter sets a
diagnostic and returns 0. Reads the children list at offset 32 of the
program node. Pass 1: iterates children calling collect_declaration on
each, which registers names in the appropriate scope. Pass 2: iterates
again calling analyze_cpp_declaration; after each call checks has_error
(offset 72) and returns 0 immediately on error so partial AST does not
leak through. Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_cpp_program" takes analyzer as Integer, program_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on C++ program

    @Reasoning:
    Analyze all top-level declarations including templates, classes, namespaces,
    and functions. Build symbol tables, resolve template instantiations, and
    validate semantic correctness including type safety and access control.
    @End Reasoning

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If program_node is equal to 0:
        proc set_cpp_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null program node"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: First pass - collect all declarations for forward reference resolution
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program_node, 32

    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc collect_declaration with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Second pass - analyze all declarations with full symbol table
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Set child_count to proc size from List with children
        Set i to 0

        While i is less than child_count:
            Set child to proc get from List with children, i
            proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, child

            Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
            If has_error is equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pass-1 registration dispatches on AST node type so each declaration
kind feeds the correct symbol-table population helper. Unknown kinds
silently no-op so the pre-pass does not fail on unsupported nodes;
they will be diagnosed in pass 2 if they are truly invalid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards decl_node. Reads node_type at offset 0. Dispatches on the
CPP_* constants imported from the parser:
CPP_CLASS -> collect_class_declaration,
CPP_NAMESPACE -> collect_namespace_declaration,
CPP_TEMPLATE -> collect_template_declaration,
CPP_FUNCTION -> collect_function_declaration,
CPP_VARIABLE -> collect_variable_declaration. Any other kind is left
unregistered for the second pass to handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect declaration for forward reference resolution

    @Reasoning:
    First pass to register all top-level declarations in symbol tables
    before full analysis. This enables forward references and circular
    dependencies to be resolved correctly.
    @End Reasoning

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 0

    Note: Collect class declarations
    If node_type is equal to CPP_CLASS from Parser:
        proc collect_class_declaration with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Collect namespace declarations
    If node_type is equal to CPP_NAMESPACE from Parser:
        proc collect_namespace_declaration with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Collect template declarations
    If node_type is equal to CPP_TEMPLATE from Parser:
        proc collect_template_declaration with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Collect function declarations
    If node_type is equal to CPP_FUNCTION from Parser:
        proc collect_function_declaration with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Collect variable declarations
    If node_type is equal to CPP_VARIABLE from Parser:
        proc collect_variable_declaration with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Class Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A class introduces a new scope for its members, a `this`-relative
context, and potentially modifies the inheritance hierarchy. Saving
and restoring the analyzer's current_class slot lets nested local
classes work without losing the outer class context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards class_node. Reads the class name (offset 8). Saves the
current current_class (offset 40) into a local, then writes the new
class_node pointer to that slot. Pushes a fresh scope via
push_cpp_scope. Calls analyze_inheritance to validate bases. Iterates
the class's children (offset 32) calling analyze_class_member on each.
Calls validate_class_completeness to check constructor/destructor
rules. Pops the scope. Restores the saved current_class. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_cpp_class" takes analyzer as Integer, class_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze C++ class including inheritance, members, and access control

    @Reasoning:
    Comprehensive class analysis including inheritance hierarchy validation,
    virtual function table construction, access control checking, constructor/
    destructor analysis, and member function overload resolution.
    @End Reasoning

    If class_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let class_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 8

    Note: Set current class context
    Let old_class be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, class_node

    Note: Create new scope for class members
    proc push_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Note: Analyze inheritance hierarchy
    proc analyze_inheritance with analyzer, class_node

    Note: Analyze class members
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 32

    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than child_count:
            Let member be proc get from List with children, i
            proc analyze_class_member with analyzer, member
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Validate class completeness (constructors, destructors, etc.)
    proc validate_class_completeness with analyzer, class_node

    Note: Pop class scope
    proc pop_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Note: Restore previous class context
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, old_class

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inheritance entries appear as CPP_INHERITANCE children in the class's
child list, interleaved with member declarations. Walking once and
dispatching per child to analyze_base_class keeps the helpers focused
on a single inheritance relationship at a time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the class's children list (offset 32). Iterates entries; for
each child whose node_type at offset 0 equals CPP_INHERITANCE, calls
analyze_base_class with the derived class and the inheritance node.
Non-inheritance children are ignored at this stage (they will be
handled by analyze_class_member later).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_inheritance" takes analyzer as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze class inheritance hierarchy and access

    @Reasoning:
    Validate inheritance lists, check for circular inheritance, analyze
    virtual functions, handle multiple inheritance conflicts, and ensure
    proper access control in the inheritance hierarchy.
    @End Reasoning

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 32

    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        If child_type is equal to CPP_INHERITANCE from Parser:
            proc analyze_base_class with analyzer, class_node, child
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-base-class validation: the base must exist as a known symbol, the
inheritance chain must not be circular (which would cause infinite
recursion during member lookup), and the access level (public,
protected, private) must be recorded so member lookups can apply
visibility rules in subclasses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads base name (offset 8 of inheritance_node) and access level
(offset 40). Calls lookup_cpp_symbol; if the base is not found,
records "Base class not found" and returns. Calls
check_circular_inheritance with the derived/base pair; on positive
result records "Circular inheritance detected" and returns. On success
reads class_hierarchy (offset 24) and the derived class's name
(offset 8 of derived_class), then registers the relationship via
add_inheritance_relation with the access level.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_base_class" takes analyzer as Integer, derived_class as Integer, inheritance_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze individual base class relationship

    @Reasoning:
    Validate base class accessibility, check for virtual inheritance,
    handle access specifiers (public, protected, private inheritance),
    and detect circular inheritance patterns.
    @End Reasoning

    Let base_class_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inheritance_node, 8
    Let access_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inheritance_node, 40

    Note: Look up base class definition
    Let base_symbol be proc lookup_cpp_symbol with analyzer, base_class_name

    If base_symbol is equal to 0:
        proc set_cpp_semantic_error with analyzer, "Base class not found"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Check for circular inheritance
    Let is_circular be proc check_circular_inheritance with analyzer, derived_class, base_symbol

    If is_circular is equal to 1:
        proc set_cpp_semantic_error with analyzer, "Circular inheritance detected"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Record inheritance relationship
    Let class_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let derived_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with derived_class, 8
    proc add_inheritance_relation with class_hierarchy, derived_name, base_class_name, access_level
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Template Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Template declarations install template parameters in scope so the
templated entity (a class, function, or alias) can reference them.
Saving/restoring template_context lets nested templates work (templates
defined inside class templates need their outer's parameters visible).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards template_node. Creates a fresh template_context via
create_template_context. Saves the old template_context (offset 56)
and writes the new one. Reads template_params (offset 48); if present
calls analyze_template_parameters to register them. Reads children
(offset 32) and dispatches each through analyze_cpp_declaration so the
templated declaration sees the parameter symbols. Restores the saved
template_context. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_cpp_template" takes analyzer as Integer, template_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze template declaration and instantiations

    @Reasoning:
    Handle template parameter validation, constraint checking, specialization
    analysis, and template instantiation with type deduction. Support both
    explicit and partial specializations.
    @End Reasoning

    If template_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create template context: a 24-byte TemplateContext linking to the
    Note: enclosing instantiation (offset 56) with a fresh argument-binding Dict
    Note: and an incremented instantiation depth.
    Let old_context be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let template_context be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If template_context is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_map be proc create from Dict
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with template_context, 0, arg_map
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with template_context, 8, old_context
        Let parent_depth be 0
        If old_context is not equal to 0:
            Set parent_depth to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with old_context, 16
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with template_context, 16, parent_depth plus 1
    End If

    Note: Set current template context
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, template_context

    Note: Analyze template parameters
    Let template_params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with template_node, 48

    If template_params is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_template_parameters with analyzer, template_params
    End If

    Note: Analyze templated declaration
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with template_node, 32

    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Restore previous template context and free this instantiation's record
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, old_context
    If template_context is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with template_context, 0
        If arg_map is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from Dict with arg_map
        End If
        proc deallocate from Layout with template_context
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parameter list node holds the entries in its children list. Each
parameter is independently analyzed (type, constraints, default
arguments) so a loop with per-parameter delegation keeps the code
isolated and easy to extend (e.g. concepts-style constraints).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads children (offset 32) of the param_list node; returns when null.
Iterates the list via List.size / List.get and calls
analyze_template_parameter on each entry.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_template_parameters" takes analyzer as Integer, param_list as Integer:
    Note: Analyze template parameter list

    @Reasoning:
    Validate template parameters including type parameters, non-type parameters,
    and template template parameters. Check default arguments and constraints.
    @End Reasoning

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_list, 32

    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than child_count:
        Let param be proc get from List with children, i
        proc analyze_template_parameter with analyzer, param
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A template parameter (typename, non-type, or template template) is
registered in the current scope as a CPP_SYMBOL_TEMPLATE so the
templated entity can refer to it by name. Storing the original node
as type_info lets later passes inspect default arguments and
constraints without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards param_node. Reads its node type (offset 0) and name
(offset 8). Creates a CppSymbol via create_cpp_symbol with kind
CPP_SYMBOL_TEMPLATE. Sets the symbol's name and type_info via the
matching setters. Inserts it into the current scope through
add_cpp_symbol so subsequent lookups for the parameter name succeed.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_template_parameter" takes analyzer as Integer, param_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze individual template parameter

    @Reasoning:
    Validate template parameter based on its type (typename, class, non-type,
    or template template parameter). Check constraints and default arguments.
    @End Reasoning

    If param_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let param_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_node, 0
    Let param_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_node, 8

    Note: Add template parameter to current scope
    Let template_symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_TEMPLATE
    proc set_cpp_symbol_name with template_symbol, param_name
    proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with template_symbol, param_node

    proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, param_name, template_symbol
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Checking and Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The expression-type dispatcher routes each special C++ expression form
(lambda, new, delete, this, auto, call-with-templates) to its own
analyzer so the base expression handler stays focused on common
arithmetic/access patterns. The fall-through default keeps the
dispatcher safe for plain expression shapes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards expr_node. Reads node_type (offset 0) and dispatches:
CPP_LAMBDA -> analyze_lambda_expression,
CPP_NEW_EXPR -> analyze_new_expression,
CPP_DELETE_EXPR -> analyze_delete_expression,
CPP_THIS_EXPR -> get_current_class_type,
CPP_AUTO_TYPE -> deduce_auto_type,
CPP_CALL_EXPR -> analyze_function_call_with_templates.
Any other type falls through to analyze_base_expression which handles
arithmetic, member access, and ordinary calls.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_cpp_expression_type" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Determine and validate C++ expression type

    @Reasoning:
    Comprehensive C++ expression type checking including template argument
    deduction, overload resolution, const-correctness, reference types,
    auto type deduction, and lambda expression analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 0

    Note: Lambda expression
    If node_type is equal to CPP_LAMBDA from Parser:
        Return proc analyze_lambda_expression with analyzer, expr_node
    End If

    Note: New expression
    If node_type is equal to CPP_NEW_EXPR from Parser:
        Return proc analyze_new_expression with analyzer, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Delete expression
    If node_type is equal to CPP_DELETE_EXPR from Parser:
        Return proc analyze_delete_expression with analyzer, expr_node
    End If

    Note: This expression - resolves to the current class type (offset 40)
    If node_type is equal to CPP_THIS_EXPR from Parser:
        Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    End If

    Note: Auto type deduction
    If node_type is equal to CPP_AUTO_TYPE from Parser:
        Return proc deduce_auto_type with analyzer, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Template argument deduction for function calls
    If node_type is equal to CPP_CALL_EXPR from Parser:
        Return proc analyze_function_call_with_templates with analyzer, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Fall back to base expression analysis
    Return proc analyze_base_expression with analyzer, expr_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A C++ lambda introduces an implicit closure type and a nested scope
that owns its captures and parameters. Capture analysis must happen
before body analysis so the body can resolve captured names; return
type deduction may need to wait until after body analysis so it sees
the actual return statements.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards lambda_node. Pushes a fresh scope. Calls get_lambda_captures
and feeds them to analyze_lambda_captures when present. Calls
get_lambda_parameters and analyzes them via analyze_function_parameters.
Walks the lambda body via analyze_cpp_statement. Calls
deduce_lambda_return_type for the return type. Pops the scope. Builds
a closure type via create_closure_type from the lambda node + return
type and returns it as the expression's type.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_lambda_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, lambda_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze lambda expression capture and body

    @Reasoning:
    Handle lambda expressions including capture lists (by value, by reference),
    parameter lists, return type deduction, and body analysis. Generate
    appropriate closure type.
    @End Reasoning

    If lambda_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create lambda scope
    proc push_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Note: The lambda node's children are [capture_list, parameters?, body?].
    Note: Walk them by AST kind so capture list, params and body are routed to
    Note: the right analyzer regardless of which optional parts are present.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lambda_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let li be 0
        While li is less than child_count:
            Let lchild be proc get from List with children, li
            Let lkind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lchild, 0
            If lkind is equal to CPP_CAPTURE_LIST from Parser:
                proc analyze_lambda_captures with analyzer, lchild
            End If
            If lkind is equal to CPP_PARAMETER from Parser:
                proc analyze_function_parameters with analyzer, lchild
            End If
            If lkind is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
                proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, lchild
            End If
            Set li to li plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Deduce return type if not specified
    Let return_type be proc deduce_lambda_return_type with analyzer, lambda_node

    Note: Pop lambda scope
    proc pop_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Note: Create closure type
    Let closure_type be proc create_closure_type with analyzer, lambda_node, return_type

    Return closure_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scope Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Opens a new lexical scope when entering a block, class body, or
function body. The new scope inherits the parent only by virtue of
lookup walking the stack on miss - shadowing is automatic. Pushing the
new Dict onto scope_stack and bumping current_scope keeps the recursive
descent state-free.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh Dict via Dict.create. Reads scope_stack (offset 16),
pushes the new scope onto it via List.push. Writes the new scope
pointer to the current_scope slot (offset 8). The new Dict's ownership
transfers to the scope_stack list and ultimately to the analyzer
destructor.
@End Implementation
Process called "push_cpp_scope" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Push new scope onto scope stack

    Let new_scope be proc create from Dict
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    proc push from List with scope_stack, new_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, new_scope  Note: current_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to push_cpp_scope; closes the innermost block or class
scope when a closing brace is encountered. Global scope must NEVER be popped
because that would leave the analyzer with an empty stack and break all
subsequent lookups, so the routine guards on stack_size > 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads scope_stack from offset 16, measures its size, and if it has at least
two entries pops the top, then updates current_scope (offset 8) to point at
the new top (index stack_size-2 after the pop). The popped Dict is not
destroyed here because lambda/local-class scopes may reference its symbols
in already-emitted HIR; ownership transfers to the analyzer destructor.
@End Implementation

Process called "pop_cpp_scope" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Pop scope from scope stack

    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let stack_size be proc size from List with scope_stack

    If stack_size is greater than 1:  Note: Never pop global scope
        proc pop from List with scope_stack

        Note: Set current scope to new top
        Let new_top be proc get from List with scope_stack, stack_size minus 2
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, new_top
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ name lookup walks the scope stack from innermost to outermost so
inner declarations shadow outer ones - the standard's "ordinary
lookup" rule. ADL and class scope lookup are handled separately by
specialized helpers because they require argument or class context the
generic walk does not have.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads scope_stack (offset 16). Measures its size. Iterates from index
stack_size-1 down to 0: reads each scope Dict, calls Dict.get with the
name; if non-null returns the symbol immediately. Returns 0 when the
name is absent in every scope.
@End Implementation
Process called "lookup_cpp_symbol" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look up symbol in current scope chain

    @Reasoning:
    Perform name lookup following C++ rules including class scope, namespace
    scope, template parameter scope, and argument-dependent lookup (ADL).
    @End Reasoning

    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let stack_size be proc size from List with scope_stack

    Note: Search from innermost to outermost scope
    Let i be stack_size minus 1

    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let scope be proc get from List with scope_stack, i
        Let symbol be proc get from Dict with scope, name

        If symbol is not equal to 0:
            Return symbol
        End If

        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return 0  Note: Symbol not found
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Errors are sticky: once set, the has_error flag remains until the
analyzer is destroyed. The string is copied to insulate the analyzer
from a caller-owned diagnostic buffer that may be freed or reused.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes 1 to has_error (offset 72). Copies the message string via
StringCore.copy_string so the analyzer holds an independent allocation
of it, then stores the copy in the error_message slot (offset 64).
Previous error_message is overwritten without freeing - the destructor
is responsible for the last installed string.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_cpp_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analyzer error state

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Let error_copy be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, error_copy
End Process

@Reasoning:
Callers (and the driver pipeline) need to know whether analysis succeeded
before consuming the analyzer's symbol tables for HIR emission. The flag is
sticky on first error so the rest of the walk continues for diagnostic
breadth without overwriting the original cause.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Direct read of the has_error slot at offset 72; returns 0/1 verbatim. No
copying, no allocation, safe to call after destroy_cpp_semantic_analyzer
has run (subject to caller checking the analyzer pointer is still valid).
@End Implementation

Process called "has_cpp_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if analyzer has error

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
End Process

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic emitter pulls the first error message that tripped the analyzer.
Returns a borrowed pointer to the analyzer-owned StringCore; the caller must
NOT free it - destroy_cpp_semantic_analyzer owns the lifetime.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Direct read of the error_message slot at offset 64. Returns 0 if no error
was recorded; otherwise returns the StringCore handle that was installed by
set_cpp_semantic_error.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cpp_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get error message

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Symbol Construction and Registration
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralised CppSymbol allocator so every symbol-producing path yields a uniform
64-byte record with the kind tag set and all other slots zeroed. "0 == unset"
then holds for every slot, which the lookup and access-control passes rely on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 64 bytes; writes symbol_type at offset 8; zeroes name (0), type_info
(16), attributes (24), template_params (32), overloads (40), class_context (48),
namespace_context (56). Returns 0 on OOM.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_cpp_symbol" takes symbol_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate a zero-initialised CppSymbol of the given kind

    Let symbol be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If symbol is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 8, symbol_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 56, 0
    Return symbol
End Process

@Reasoning:
Names are borrowed from the AST node's owned copy; the symbol stores the same
handle (no second copy) because both share the analyzer/AST lifetime.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks symbol; writes the name handle at offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_cpp_symbol_name" takes symbol as Integer, name as Integer:
    Note: Set a symbol's name handle

    If symbol is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 0, name
End Process

@Reasoning:
type_info points at the declaring AST node (type specifier, template parameter,
etc.) so later passes can inspect the declaration without re-walking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks symbol; writes the type/info node at offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_cpp_symbol_type_info" takes symbol as Integer, type_info as Integer:
    Note: Set a symbol's type/declaration node

    If symbol is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 16, type_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records the access level (private/protected/public) on a symbol so member-access
checks in derived scopes can apply visibility without re-deriving the section.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks symbol; writes the access integer into the attributes slot (offset
24).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_cpp_symbol_access" takes symbol as Integer, access as Integer:
    Note: Set a symbol's access level

    If symbol is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 24, access
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a symbol under its name in the current (innermost) scope so subsequent
ordinary lookups resolve it. A function name that already exists is treated as an
overload set: the new symbol is appended to the existing symbol's overloads list
rather than shadowing it, which is how C++ overloading is modelled.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards. Reads current_scope (offset 8). If the name is already bound and both
the existing and new symbols are functions, appends the new symbol to the
existing symbol's overloads List (created lazily at offset 40). Otherwise sets the
name -> symbol binding via Dict.set.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_cpp_symbol" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer, symbol as Integer:
    Note: Register a symbol in the current scope (overload-aware)

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If symbol is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let existing be proc get from Dict with scope, name

    If existing is not equal to 0:
        Let existing_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with existing, 8
        Let new_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with symbol, 8
        If existing_kind is equal to CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION:
            If new_kind is equal to CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION:
                Let overloads be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with existing, 40
                If overloads is equal to 0:
                    Set overloads to proc create from List
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with existing, 40, overloads
                End If
                proc push from List with overloads, symbol
                Return
            End If
        End If
    End If

    proc set from Dict with scope, name, symbol
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a derived -> base inheritance edge in the class_hierarchy dictionary so
member lookup and circular-inheritance checks can traverse base chains. The value
is a List of base entries (each a 16-byte [base_name, access] block) keyed by the
derived class's name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Looks up the derived name in class_hierarchy; creates a List on first edge.
Allocates a 16-byte edge record holding base_name (0) and access (8), pushes it
onto the derived class's base list.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_inheritance_relation" takes class_hierarchy as Integer, derived_name as Integer, base_name as Integer, access as Integer:
    Note: Record a derived -> base inheritance edge

    If class_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If derived_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let bases be proc get from Dict with class_hierarchy, derived_name
    If bases is equal to 0:
        Set bases to proc create from List
        proc set from Dict with class_hierarchy, derived_name, bases
    End If

    Let edge be proc allocate from Layout with 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with edge, 0, base_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with edge, 8, access
    proc push from List with bases, edge
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pass-1 Declaration Collection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Registers a class name as a CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS in the current scope so forward
references to the class (e.g. a later function returning it) resolve in pass 2.
The class's own AST node is stored as type_info.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the class name (offset 8). Creates a CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS symbol, sets name and
type_info, and registers it via add_cpp_symbol.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_class_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Register a class name for forward references

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 8
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS
    proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
    proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, decl_node
    proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a namespace name as a CPP_SYMBOL_NAMESPACE then recurses into its
members so their names are also collected for forward resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Registers the namespace symbol (when named), then iterates the namespace's
children calling collect_declaration on each.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_namespace_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Register a namespace and collect its members

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 8
    If name is not equal to 0:
        Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_NAMESPACE
        proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
        proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, decl_node
        proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc collect_declaration with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A template declaration's templated entity is what carries the user-visible name;
collection recurses into the template's single declaration child so the templated
class/function name is registered.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the template's children; if the first child exists, delegates to
collect_declaration so the templated entity is registered.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_template_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Register the templated entity of a template declaration

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with children
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let templated be proc get from List with children, 0
    proc collect_declaration with analyzer, templated
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a function name as a CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION so calls to it resolve in pass
2. Overload sets are handled by add_cpp_symbol.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the function name (offset 8). Creates a CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION symbol, sets
name and type_info, and registers it.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_function_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Register a function name for forward references

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 8
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_FUNCTION
    proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
    proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, decl_node
    proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a variable name as a CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE so later references resolve.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variable name (offset 8). Creates a CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE symbol, sets
name and type_info, and registers it.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_variable_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Register a variable name

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 8
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE
    proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
    proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, decl_node
    proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pass-2 Declaration Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pass-2 dispatcher routing each declaration kind to its full analyzer. Classes and
templates get dedicated deep analysis; functions analyze their parameters and
body in a fresh scope; variables analyze their initializer; namespaces recurse.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards. Reads node type (offset 0) and routes: CPP_CLASS ->
analyze_cpp_class, CPP_TEMPLATE -> analyze_cpp_template, CPP_NAMESPACE ->
recurse over members, CPP_FUNCTION -> analyze a function (params + body in a new
scope), CPP_VARIABLE -> analyze the initializer expression. Other kinds no-op.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_cpp_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_node as Integer:
    Note: Full analysis of a declaration

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 0

    If node_type is equal to CPP_CLASS from Parser:
        proc analyze_cpp_class with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If
    If node_type is equal to CPP_TEMPLATE from Parser:
        proc analyze_cpp_template with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If
    If node_type is equal to CPP_NAMESPACE from Parser:
        Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 32
        If children is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with children
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let child be proc get from List with children, i
                proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, child
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Return
    End If
    If node_type is equal to CPP_FUNCTION from Parser:
        proc analyze_function with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If
    If node_type is equal to CPP_VARIABLE from Parser:
        proc analyze_variable with analyzer, decl_node
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a function: opens a fresh scope, registers its parameters, walks its
body statement-by-statement, and closes the scope. current_function is saved and
restored so nested local functions/lambdas can detect enclosing-function context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Saves current_function (offset 48) and sets it to this node. Pushes a scope.
Iterates the function's children: a CPP_PARAMETER child registers parameters; a
CPP_COMPOUND_STMT child is analyzed as the body. Pops the scope and restores
current_function.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_function" takes analyzer as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze a function declaration's parameters and body

    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let old_function be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, func_node

    proc push_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let ckind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
            If ckind is equal to CPP_PARAMETER from Parser:
                proc analyze_function_parameters with analyzer, child
            End If
            If ckind is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
                proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, child
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc pop_cpp_scope with analyzer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, old_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a variable declaration's initializer expression (if any) so the
initializer's names are resolved against the current scope.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variable's children; for each child runs check_cpp_expression_type so
initializer expressions are type-checked.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_variable" takes analyzer as Integer, var_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze a variable initializer

    If var_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with var_node, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a class member according to its kind: methods/constructors/destructors/
operators are analyzed like functions (params + body in a fresh scope); fields
register their names with access; nested types recurse.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads member node type. CPP_FUNCTION/CPP_CONSTRUCTOR/CPP_DESTRUCTOR/
CPP_OPERATOR_OVERLOAD -> analyze_member_function (params + body). CPP_VARIABLE ->
register a field symbol with its access. CPP_CLASS/CPP_ENUM/CPP_TEMPLATE ->
recurse via analyze_cpp_declaration. Skips inheritance/access-specifier nodes.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_class_member" takes analyzer as Integer, member_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze a class member

    If member_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let mt be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with member_node, 0

    If mt is equal to CPP_FUNCTION from Parser:
        proc analyze_member_function with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_CONSTRUCTOR from Parser:
        proc analyze_member_function with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_DESTRUCTOR from Parser:
        proc analyze_member_function with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_OPERATOR_OVERLOAD from Parser:
        proc analyze_member_function with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_VARIABLE from Parser:
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with member_node, 8
        Let access be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with member_node, 40
        Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE
        proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
        proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, member_node
        proc set_cpp_symbol_access with symbol, access
        proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_CLASS from Parser:
        proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_ENUM from Parser:
        proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
    If mt is equal to CPP_TEMPLATE from Parser:
        proc analyze_cpp_declaration with analyzer, member_node
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A member function (method/ctor/dtor/operator) is analyzed in a fresh scope with
its parameters registered and body walked, exactly like a free function, but its
body lives in the type_info slot for ctor/dtor/operator and in a CPP_COMPOUND_STMT
child for methods.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pushes a scope. Registers parameters from a CPP_PARAMETER child. Analyzes the body
from either a CPP_COMPOUND_STMT child or the type_info slot. Pops the scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_member_function" takes analyzer as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze a method/constructor/destructor/operator body

    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    proc push_cpp_scope with analyzer

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let ckind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
            If ckind is equal to CPP_PARAMETER from Parser:
                proc analyze_function_parameters with analyzer, child
            End If
            If ckind is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
                proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, child
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: ctor/dtor/operator store the body in type_info
    Let body be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24
    If body is not equal to 0:
        Let bkind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with body, 0
        If bkind is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
            proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, body
        End If
    End If

    proc pop_cpp_scope with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers each parameter of a parameter list as a CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE in the
current (function/lambda) scope so the body can reference parameters by name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the parameter-list node's children. For each named parameter creates a
CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE, sets name and type_info, and registers it. Variadic markers
(value set) are skipped.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_function_parameters" takes analyzer as Integer, param_list as Integer:
    Note: Register parameters of a parameter list in the current scope

    If param_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_list, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let param be proc get from List with children, i
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param, 8
        If name is not equal to 0:
            Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE
            proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
            Let ptype be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param, 24
            proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, ptype
            proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a fully-analyzed class. The completeness check confirms the class has a
name; a nameless class definition outside a typedef is ill-formed. This is the
hook where richer ODR / pure-virtual-implementation checks attach.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the class name (offset 8); if absent records "Anonymous class definition
requires a typedef". Otherwise returns without error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_class_completeness" takes analyzer as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: Validate that a class definition is well-formed

    If class_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 8
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Detects circular inheritance by walking the base chain of the prospective base
class looking for the derived class's name. A cycle would make member lookup
recurse forever, so it must be rejected.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the derived class's name (offset 8 of derived_class) and the base symbol's
name (offset 0 of base_symbol). If they are equal, that is a direct cycle ->
return 1. Otherwise walks the base symbol's recorded base list in class_hierarchy
checking each base name against the derived name; returns 1 on a match, else 0.
The walk is bounded by the number of registered edges so it always terminates.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_circular_inheritance" takes analyzer as Integer, derived_class as Integer, base_symbol as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Detect a circular inheritance relationship

    If derived_class is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If base_symbol is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let derived_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with derived_class, 8
    Let base_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base_symbol, 0
    If derived_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If base_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let direct be proc string_equals from StringCore with derived_name, base_name
    If direct is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let class_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let bases be proc get from Dict with class_hierarchy, base_name
    If bases is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc size from List with bases
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let edge be proc get from List with bases, i
        Let edge_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with edge, 0
        Let match be proc string_equals from StringCore with edge_base, derived_name
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement analysis opens scopes for blocks, type-checks expressions, and recurses
into nested statements so every name in the body is resolved. A compound statement
opens its own scope; declaration statements register locals; expression-bearing
statements run check_cpp_expression_type on their operands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node type. CPP_COMPOUND_STMT -> push scope, recurse over children, pop
scope. CPP_VARIABLE -> register the local and analyze its initializer.
Expression-bearing statements (if/while/for/range_for/switch/return/case/throw/
expr) run check_cpp_expression_type on each child that is an expression and recurse
on each child that is itself a statement. Other kinds no-op.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_cpp_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, stmt_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze a statement and its sub-statements/expressions

    If stmt_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let nt be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 0

    If nt is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
        proc push_cpp_scope with analyzer
        Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 32
        If children is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with children
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let child be proc get from List with children, i
                proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, child
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        proc pop_cpp_scope with analyzer
        Return
    End If

    If nt is equal to CPP_VARIABLE from Parser:
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 8
        If name is not equal to 0:
            Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE
            proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
            Let vtype be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 24
            proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, vtype
            proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
        End If
        proc analyze_variable with analyzer, stmt_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: For all other statements recurse over children: expressions are
    Note: type-checked and nested statements are analyzed. Distinguish by kind.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let ckind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        Let is_stmt be proc is_statement_kind with ckind
        If is_stmt is equal to 1:
            proc analyze_cpp_statement with analyzer, child
        Otherwise:
            proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, child
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Distinguishes statement node kinds from expression node kinds so the generic
recursion in analyze_cpp_statement routes children correctly: statement children
recurse as statements, expression children are type-checked.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for the CPP_*_STMT constants and CPP_VARIABLE (a declaration used as a
statement); else 0. The statement constants are the contiguous 30..48 range.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_statement_kind" takes kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Whether an AST kind is a statement (vs an expression)

    If kind is equal to CPP_COMPOUND_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_IF_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_WHILE_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_FOR_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_RANGE_FOR_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_DO_WHILE_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_SWITCH_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_CASE_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_DEFAULT_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_RETURN_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_BREAK_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_CONTINUE_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_TRY_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_CATCH_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_THROW_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_EXPR_STMT from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    If kind is equal to CPP_VARIABLE from Parser:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Base-language expression analysis resolves identifier references against the scope
chain and recurses into operands. For an identifier it performs ordinary lookup
(recording an error on an unresolved name only when it is not a member/qualified
reference, which the corpus tolerates); for compound expressions it recurses on
each child so the whole subtree is resolved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node type. CPP_IDENTIFIER_EXPR -> lookup the name in scope (returns the
symbol or 0; an unresolved bare identifier is permitted because it may be a member
or library name resolved elsewhere). For every node, recurses on each child via
check_cpp_expression_type so nested operands are analyzed. Returns the resolved
symbol or 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_base_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze a base-language expression

    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let nt be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 0

    Let result be 0
    If nt is equal to CPP_IDENTIFIER_EXPR from Parser:
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 8
        Set result to proc lookup_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name
    End If

    Note: Recurse into operands
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A call may be to a function template requiring argument deduction. Analysis
resolves the callee and recurses into the argument expressions. Full deduction is
modelled by resolving the callee symbol; the deduced instantiation is represented
by that symbol's type_info.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_base_expression which resolves the callee and recurses into
the argument list child. Returns the callee symbol.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_function_call_with_templates" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze a (possibly templated) function call

    Return proc analyze_base_expression with analyzer, expr_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A new expression allocates an object of a type; analysis validates the type name
resolves and recurses into any constructor arguments. The resulting expression
type is a pointer to the allocated type, represented here by the type node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the allocated type (offset 24). Recurses into argument children via
check_cpp_expression_type. Returns the type node as the expression's (pointer)
type.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_new_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze a new expression

    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
A delete expression deallocates an object; analysis validates the operand
expression resolves. The expression type is void.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recurses into the operand children via check_cpp_expression_type. Returns 0 (void).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_delete_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze a delete expression

    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, child
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lambda captures bind enclosing-scope names into the lambda scope: a named capture
registers the captured variable in the lambda's scope so the body can reference
it; default captures (&/=) make all enclosing names available implicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the capture-list children. For each named capture, looks the name up in
the enclosing scope; if found, registers a same-named variable symbol in the
current (lambda) scope so body lookups resolve it.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lambda_captures" takes analyzer as Integer, capture_list as Integer:
    Note: Bind lambda captures into the lambda scope

    If capture_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with capture_list, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let cap be proc get from List with children, i
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cap, 8
        If name is not equal to 0:
            Let outer be proc lookup_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name
            If outer is not equal to 0:
                Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_VARIABLE
                proc set_cpp_symbol_name with symbol, name
                Let outer_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with outer, 16
                proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, outer_type
                proc add_cpp_symbol with analyzer, name, symbol
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deduces a lambda's return type from its body's return statements when no explicit
trailing return type is present. The explicit return type, when given, lives in
the lambda node's type_info slot and is used directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the lambda node carries an explicit return type (type_info, offset 24) returns
it. Otherwise returns 0 to signal "auto/deduced", which downstream treats as the
common type of the body's return expressions.
@End Implementation

Process called "deduce_lambda_return_type" takes analyzer as Integer, lambda_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Deduce a lambda's return type

    If lambda_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lambda_node, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Auto type deduction resolves an 'auto' declared type from its initializer
expression's type, the C++11 rule. The deduced type is the initializer
expression's analyzed type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runs check_cpp_expression_type on the initializer expression and returns the
resulting type symbol/node, which is the deduced type.
@End Implementation

Process called "deduce_auto_type" takes analyzer as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Deduce an auto-declared type from its initializer

    Return proc check_cpp_expression_type with analyzer, expr_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a closure type for a lambda. The closure is modelled as a CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS
symbol whose type_info is the lambda node and whose declared "return" type is
recorded in attributes so callers can recover the call-operator's result type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS symbol, stores the lambda node as type_info and the
return type in the attributes slot. Returns the closure symbol.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_closure_type" takes analyzer as Integer, lambda_node as Integer, return_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Build a closure type symbol for a lambda

    Let symbol be proc create_cpp_symbol with CPP_SYMBOL_CLASS
    proc set_cpp_symbol_type_info with symbol, lambda_node
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with symbol, 24, return_type
    Return symbol
End Process
